but the amount that space is expanding
and contracting by is absolutely

00:02:40.520 --> 00:02:44.920
minuscule. So this big result that came up
with this thing that they detected - the amount

00:02:44.920 --> 00:02:49.320
by which space was expanding over the
many kilometers of their detector was

00:02:49.330 --> 00:02:54.030
less than the diameter of the nucleus of
an atom. So it's an absolutely tiny - infact

00:02:54.030 --> 00:02:58.250
that's why we don't - sort of notice them going past 'cause if they were big effects, you know you'd see

00:02:58.260 --> 00:03:02.500
kind of space doing all sorts of weird things. But because they're so tiny we just don't see them.

00:03:02.500 --> 00:03:06.660
It's just amazing, I mean
the numbers involved, the timing involved -

00:03:06.670 --> 00:03:15.360
it's a spectacular event so - a billion light years
away - four hundred and fifty megaparsecs away -

00:03:15.360 --> 00:03:22.260
So a billion years ago, two black holes which
were each of them thirty times the mass

00:03:22.260 --> 00:03:26.820
of the Sun, okay? Which is unusual apparently in its
