00:10:02.149 --> 00:10:06.930
detecting in these interferometers. There's
two things that save them: one is that

00:10:06.930 --> 00:10:10.259
actually it has - the things that you're
looking for - so things like these black

00:10:10.269 --> 00:10:14.160
hole signatures - have a very
characteristic shape to them that the

00:10:14.160 --> 00:10:18.300
way that the oscillations increase and
decrease in amplitude with time - has this very

00:10:18.300 --> 00:10:20.740
classic signature to it that tells you
the kind of thing you're looking for -

00:10:20.740 --> 00:10:24.240
so they know what sort of thing to look for,
and then the second thing that saved them

00:10:24.240 --> 00:10:26.560
is that there isn't just one
interferometer, there's two working at the

00:10:26.560 --> 00:10:29.280
same time a large distance apart from
one another -

00:10:29.290 --> 00:10:33.980
and so the chances of the same
pathological truck going past both of them

00:10:33.980 --> 00:10:36.340
at the same time producing
something that looks exactly like a

00:10:36.340 --> 00:10:39.720
black hole merger signature is at that point astronomically small -

00:10:39.720 --> 00:10:42.080
so they can,
by doing this kind of coincidence

00:10:42.089 --> 00:10:46.170
thing of detecting it in both detectors
almost simultaneously - tells them that

00:10:46.170 --> 00:10:49.540
actually they have detected a real
astrophysical result. One of the upsides

00:10:49.540 --> 00:10:53.200
to actually having two detectors; if the
gravitational wave is coming from over

00:10:53.200 --> 00:10:57.560
here somewhere - it'll hit one detector
first and then a bit later it'll hit the other detector

00:10:57.560 --> 00:11:02.100
So the wave came through, hit
Louisiana first, and then the

00:11:02.110 --> 00:11:05.660
light travel time - because they're going
at the speed of light - it then passed

00:11:05.660 --> 00:11:10.790
